'''Monitored Emergency Use of Unregistered and Investigational Interventions''' ('''MEURI''') is an [[ethical protocol]] developed by the [[World Health Organization]] to evaluate the potential use of experimental drugs in the event of [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern|public health emergencies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/emergencies/ebola/MEURI-Ebola.pdf|title=Notes for the record: Consultation on Monitored Emergency Use of Unregistered and Investigational Interventions for Ebola Virus Disease (EVD)|publisher=World Health Organization|date=17 May 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> The protocol was created by the [[WHO Ebola Ethics Working Group]] in 2014<ref>{{Cite journal|author=WHO Ethics Working Group|date=2014|title=Ethical issues related to study design for trials on therapeutics for Ebola Virus Disease: WHO Ethics Working Group meeting 20–21 October, summary of discussion|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/handle/10665/137509|language=en|publisher=World Health Organization}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Calain|first=Philippe|date=2018-01-01|title=The Ebola clinical trials: a precedent for research ethics in disasters|url=http://jme.bmj.com/content/44/1/3|journal=Journal of Medical Ethics|language=en|volume=44|issue=1|pages=3–8|doi=10.1136/medethics-2016-103474|issn=0306-6800|pmid=27573153}}</ref> in the context of the [[2014 West Africa Ebola outbreak]]. The WHO recommends that the term be preferred to the term "[[compassionate use]]" or "[[expanded access]]" for the controlled use of unregistered treatments in public health emergency measures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Richardson|first=Thomas|last2=Johnston|first2=Andrew McDonald|last3=Draper|first3=Heather|date=2017-01-17|title=A Systematic Review of Ebola Treatment Trials to Assess the Extent to Which They Adhere to Ethical Guidelines |journal=PLOS ONE|language=en|volume=12|issue=1|pages=e0168975|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0168975 |pmc=5240928|pmid=28095476}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alirol|first=Emilie|last2=Kuesel|first2=Annette C.|last3=Guraiib|first3=Maria Magdalena|last4=dela Fuente-Núñez|first4=Vânia|last5=Saxena|first5=Abha|last6=Gomes|first6=Melba F.|date=2017-06-26|title=Ethics review of studies during public health emergencies - the experience of the WHO ethics review committee during the Ebola virus disease epidemic|journal=BMC Medical Ethics|volume=18|doi=10.1186/s12910-017-0201-1|issn=1472-6939|pmc=5485606|pmid=28651650}}</ref>
