The '''reduced enamel epithelium''', sometimes called '''reduced dental epithelium''', overlies a [[tooth development|developing]] [[tooth]] and is formed by two layers: a layer of [[ameloblast]] [[cell (biology)|cells]] and the adjacent layer of [[cuboidal cell]]s (outer enamel epithelium) from the [[dental lamina]]. As the cells of the reduced enamel epithelium degenerate, the tooth is revealed progressively with its eruption into the [[mouth]]. The degeneration of reduced enamel epithelium also mediates the initial [[epithelium|epithelial]] attachment to the tooth, which is called the junctional epithelium.
The reduced enamel epithelium consist of:
* [[Inner enamel epithelium]] * [[Outer enamel epithelium]]
